	<h1 id="char">Character</h1>
        <p>
          Any time an ML opens at <em>SB/n</em>, the result is
          calculated as follows.  The intention is to average out
          excessive attribute rolls that should not be changing skill
          levels by various multiples.  (E.g. with 18 the SB is
          already worth SBx3 for 6, which seems unlikely as far as
          education is concerned.  The rule presented here levels some
          of that.
        </p>
        <ul class="explain">
          <li>
            <b>n=1</b>: Simply take SB.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>n=2</b>: Calculate SB', which is SB increased or
            decreased by 1 to bring it closer to 10.  (Instead of
            passing 10, take SB'=10.)  Then take SB + SB' as result.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>n=3</b>: Calculate SB'', which is SB increased or
            decreased by 2 to bring it closer to 10.  (Instead of
            passing 10, take SB''=10.)  Then take SB + SB' + SB'' as
            result.
          </li>
          <li>
            ...
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
